  accentWord="Loft Conversion"
  subhead="It is 10:30am on a Thursday. You are fitting the final steel purlin in a dormer conversion in Witney — the telehandler is lifting the beam, your crew is guiding it onto the bearing plates, and you are checking the alignment against the structural drawing from the scaffold platform. Two calls come in between 10 and 11am. Your phone is in your jacket on the landing below, three floors down. Without Missed Call Text Back, both callers hear voicemail. One leaves a message — 'want a loft conversion quote' — the other hangs up. By noon the unknown number has called another company. With it, both receive a text within seconds. The first replies: 'Hi — want a rear dormer on our 3-bed Victorian terrace in Jericho. Need a bedroom and en-suite. Both neighbours' lofts are converted already. Can you survey?' At 12:15 you read the reply and call her. You book a Saturday morning survey."
  scenario="It is 2:45pm on a Saturday in June. You have been working all day on a hip-to-gable conversion — replacing the existing hip roof tiles with a new gable structure, a physically demanding job requiring concentration and both hands. Three calls come in during the afternoon. Without Missed Call Text Back, you check at 4pm: three missed calls, one voicemail saying 'hi, interested in a loft conversion.' You try the voicemail number — engaged. The other two are unknown numbers. Three potential conversions, two completely unrecoverable. With Missed Call Text Back, all three received texts within seconds of calling. The first replies at 2:50: 'rear dormer on a semi in OX14, measured 2.4m ridge height, want a bedroom and shower room.' The second at 3:05: 'hip-to-gable on a 1960s detached in Headington, want to maximise space for two bedrooms, have not measured yet.' The third at 3:30: 'looking at converting the loft of a bungalow in Eynsham, want a bedroom and office up there, worried about staircase position.' At 4pm you wash the dust off your hands and open three leads — a semi dormer with measurements, a detached hip-to-gable, and a bungalow conversion with staircase concerns — all with property type, location, and project context. You call all three before 5pm and book Monday, Tuesday, and Wednesday surveys."
  benefits={benefits}
